=== Career Progression Pathways

*Within 2-3 years:*
- *Actuarial Analyst*: Completing Part I and progressing through Part II exams, taking ownership of specific pricing or reserving workstreams
- *Specialization*: Choosing focus area (pricing, reserving, capital, product development) and building deeper expertise

*Within 3-5 years:*
- *Senior Actuarial Analyst*: Completing Part II and Part III exams toward Associate (AIAA) qualification, leading projects independently, beginning to present to pricing committee and management

For detailed pathways, see Senior Analyst and Actuary sections below.

*Alternative paths in first 2-3 years:*
- Move to actuarial consulting firm (Mercer, Willis Towers Watson, Deloitte) for exposure to multiple clients and varied projects
- Join reinsurer (Swiss Re, Munich Re) for different perspective on insurance risk
- Transfer to superannuation actuarial role (different risk profile, long-term investment focus)
- Move to regulatory role at APRA (prudential supervision of insurance industry)
- Transition to data science/analytics role in insurance or broader financial services

