== 2. Actuarial Analyst / Senior Analyst

=== Hierarchy Level
2-5 years of experience, progressing through professional exams toward Associate of the Institute of Actuaries of Australia (AIAA)

=== Key Activities and Responsibilities
- *Independent Project Leadership*: Owning complete pricing reviews or reserving analyses with limited supervision
- *Methodology Development*: Designing and implementing new models and analytical approaches
- *Stakeholder Presentation*: Presenting findings and recommendations to pricing committee, underwriting leadership, and management
- *Technical Mentoring*: Supervising and reviewing work of graduate actuaries
- *Regulatory Reporting*: Contributing to APRA submissions, Financial Condition Reports, AASB 17 valuations
- *Strategic Analysis*: Supporting business strategy with portfolio profitability analysis, market opportunity assessment, capital optimization

=== Required Skills Development

Beyond graduate level:
- *Advanced Actuarial Techniques*: GLM, GAM, machine learning for pricing and claims prediction, stochastic reserving methods, catastrophe modelling
- *Business Acumen*: Understanding of company strategy, competitive dynamics, underwriting profitability drivers, management priorities
- *Communication*: Translating technical analysis into clear business recommendations for non-actuarial executives
- *Professional Judgment*: Selecting appropriate models, setting reasonable assumptions, balancing precision with practicality
- *Exam Progression*: Completing Part II and Part III to achieve AIAA Associate qualification (typically 3-5 years from starting exams)

=== Typical Work Patterns
Similar distribution to graduate but with more stakeholder management (25-30% in meetings), independent analytical work (50-60%), and mentoring responsibilities (10-15%). Leading pricing refreshes, conducting profit studies, presenting recommendations to senior management.

=== Day in the Life - Senior Analyst

Similar structure to graduate but with greater autonomy and strategic input. Typical day includes:
- Leading pricing reviews independently and presenting recommendations to pricing committee
- Conducting advanced statistical modelling (GLMs, decision trees, geographic rating)
- Reviewing and mentoring graduate actuaries' work
- Participating in quarterly reserve reviews with Chief Actuary
- Contributing to strategic discussions on new products or market opportunities

Hours typically 8:30am-6:00pm with extension during quarter-end reporting (can extend to 7-8pm for 2-3 weeks during March, June, September, December). Still balancing work with exam study for Part III.

=== Career Progression
*Within 2-3 years*: Actuary role (Fellow track) with responsibility for signing statutory actuarial reports, or specialization as pricing actuary, reserving actuary, or capital actuary.

