== 3. Actuary

=== Hierarchy Level
5-8 years of experience, achieved AIAA Associate qualification, progressing toward Fellowship (FIAA)

=== Key Activities and Responsibilities
- *Signing Authority*: Appointed Actuary role under APRA requirements, signing Financial Condition Reports and providing professional advice to Board
- *Team Leadership*: Managing small team of analysts and graduates, delegating work, providing technical guidance
- *Model Governance*: Ensuring actuarial models comply with professional standards, internal validation, regulatory requirements
- *Strategic Advisory*: Advising senior management and Board on risk appetite, capital management, business strategy
- *External Representation*: Presenting at industry conferences, participating in Actuaries Institute working parties, engaging with regulators
- *Product Innovation*: Leading development of new insurance products and pricing structures
- *Reinsurance Strategy*: Designing optimal reinsurance structures, negotiating with reinsurers, modeling capital efficiency

=== Key Skills
Actuaries combine deep technical expertise with business leadership. Strong professional judgment in setting assumptions, ability to communicate complex concepts to Board and regulators, strategic thinking about portfolio management and risk appetite, and increasing commercial awareness of market dynamics and competitive positioning.

=== Typical Work Patterns
Work balance shifts toward stakeholder management (35-40%), strategic analysis (25-30%), team leadership (20-25%), with less hands-on technical work (15-20%). Presenting regularly to Board and executive committee, engaging with APRA on regulatory matters, representing company externally. Hours typically 8:30am-6:30pm with periodic late nights during regulatory reporting cycles.

=== Career Progression
*Within 2-4 years*: Senior Actuary or specialist leadership role (Chief Pricing Actuary, Chief Reserving Actuary), or broader management role in underwriting or corporate strategy.

