== 4. Senior Actuary / Chief Actuary

=== Hierarchy Level
8-15 years of experience, Fellow of the Institute of Actuaries of Australia (FIAA), senior leadership role

=== Key Responsibilities
- Serving as Chief Actuary or Appointed Actuary with ultimate responsibility for actuarial advice to Board
- Leading actuarial function (team of 10-30 actuaries depending on company size)
- Setting technical strategy and methodology standards across pricing, reserving, capital
- Primary interface with APRA on prudential matters and technical compliance
- Advising Board and CEO on risk appetite, capital strategy, business planning
- Representing company on industry bodies and with rating agencies
- Thought leadership on emerging risks (climate, cyber, pandemic) and industry trends

Senior actuaries operate with significant autonomy, balancing technical rigor with commercial reality and regulatory requirements. Focus on strategic direction (35-40%), Board and executive engagement (30-35%), team development (15-20%), and external representation (10-15%).

=== Career Progression
*Chief Actuary* is often the pinnacle of technical actuarial career, though some progress to:
- *Chief Risk Officer*: Broader enterprise risk management role beyond insurance risk
- *Chief Financial Officer*: Leveraging financial acumen and risk expertise
- *CEO*: Particularly in mid-sized insurers, actuarial background provides strong foundation
- *Board Director*: Non-executive director roles leveraging actuarial and risk expertise

